<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900924-0141</DOCNO><DOCID>900924-0141.</DOCID><HL>   William Galvin Sentenced   To 32-Month Prison Term</HL><DATE>09/24/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defense consultant William Galvin wassentenced to 32 months in prison after pleading guilty tobribing two senior Pentagon officials to influence theawarding of lucrative military contracts.   Mr. Galvin, a major figure in the defense procurementscandal, was also fined $10,000 by U.S. District Judge ClaudeM. Hilton in Alexandra, Va., on his guilty plea to charges ofconspiracy, bribery and tax evasion.</LP><TEXT>   Along with another 32-month prison term given to a formerUnisys Corp. executive, Mr. Galvin's sentence was the longestimposed in the long-running probe of Pentagon procurementfraud.   Mr. Galvin, 59 years old, faced a possible 40-year prisonsentence and fines of as much as $1 million. But prosecutors,citing Mr. Galvin's &quot;extraordinary cooperation&quot; with theinvestigation, asked Judge Hilton to impose a shorter prisonterm. Assistant U.S. Attorney Joseph Aronica told JudgeHilton that Mr. Galvin is expected to be &quot;a critical witnessin future prosecutions.&quot;   Mr. Galvin pleaded guilty in March to arranging paymentsthrough a Swiss bank account to then-Assistant Navy SecretaryMelvyn R. Paisley for helping an Israeli company sellpilotless intelligence airplanes to the Pentagon. Mr. Galvinalso said he paid $123,100 from 1983 to 1985 to a friend ofVictor D. Cohen, then a deputy assistant Air Force secretary,knowing that some of the money would be given to Mr. Cohen toinfluence the awarding of a contract on radar-warningdevices. Mr. Paisley and Mr. Cohen haven't been charged butboth are under investigation.   Under his plea, Mr. Galvin agreed to pay the InternalRevenue Service $648,548 in back taxes and interest.</TEXT></DOC>